                    <span>I read every Dan Brown book and Digital Fortress is the last one so far. I did like it better than Deception Point, but it pales in comparison to the Langdon novels. 
<br />In Digital Fortress we are presented a dilemma by a hacker that has hacked into National Securities (NSA) most powerful computer. If the Hacker gets his way electronic destruction will occurr unless the heros can locate the special code that can unlock it and end it's countdown. Problem is the Code is in Spain and there are sabateurs out there doing thier best to make sure the code falls into the wrong hands.
<br /> The pace of DF was well maintained, the clues were fair, I didn't care for the hoaky dialogue, as well has the 2 dimensional chacters. But over all it was a decent read, just to fluffy for my tastes.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">For me, it's rather fantasy than fiction...</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>3</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>0</span>
                      /
                      <span>0</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-05-15</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>I am an information technology student, and base on my knowledge I can tell you Dan Brown did not do his research well, there are several things that are not right about the "facts" of this book. Many of them are merely technical, but others are really bad mistakes that are the base of the story. For instance, you can only do a brute force attack on an encrypted text if you know the algorithm used to encrypt it. So if they didn't knew the algorithm used to encrypt the "unbreakable code" because it was encrypted with itself, trying to break it with TRNSLTR was senseless. Second, if with a key you could decrypt the code, you need a decryptor program for that algorithm, and so the decryption part of the algorithm needed to be decrypted for the "key" to be useful. If the whole algorithm was encrypted with itself, then there was no way to decrypt it even having the key. So there was no sense in putting it in TRNSLTR or in any computer, besides, the idea that it was in fact a virus and not really an unbreakable code came to my mind at the very begining of the story, so if I am just a student, someone as "experienced" as Strathmore could not be so stupid to make that mistake. Next, the "Caesar code" is simply called a "column transposition" algorithm and was not used in Rome. I could just list tons of other facts to destroy Dan Brown's story here, but my review would get very boring. Why did I gave it 3 stars then? It's a very entertaining story, as Dan Brown's normally are, so even with those severe mistakes I could enjoy the book, but it could have been a lot better if the "facts" were more real.
<br />
<br />An additional thing: for those who care about it an "unbreakable code" actually exists: if you use any algorithm, no matter which, with a key longer than the cleartext, you will have more keys than cleartexts and that would make a brute force attack useless because by trying every possible key you will also get every possible cleartext, and there's no way you could identify the real one.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Tries hard - falls flat</div>
