                    <span>What an absolute crap - totally technically drab, and tries hard to create a calamity when there is none. You keep hanging with a faint glimmer of hope that it will pick up the pace - you secretly hope David will get out of Spain and do something interesting, and pray boss Stathmore doesnt turn out to be the villian, you would think that it is too cliched for Dan Brown to work on plot twists so dumb - but yes, he did, he went over the top. His climax is dumb squid, characters unidimensional, and greatest crime of all - made up crisis - you almost feel sorry for him when he tries again and again to whip up the tempo - he throws insane roadblocks, predictable twists, and you can hear him plead "Please be afraid - this is the end of the world" - Sorry Dan, maybe yours, not ours. 
<br />[from my blog: http://www.ofview.com/?p=42]
<br /></span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Inaccurate, uninvolving pulp techno thriller.</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>2</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>1</span>
                      /
                      <span>3</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-05-13</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>If you are thinking of picking up this book because you'd like a cerebral thriller, don't. It's fast paced (2 day read) but very shallow and not particularly well researched.
<br />
<br />The fact that the Corgi edition paperback of "Digital Fortress" is covered with quotes praising "The DaVinci Code" and yet contains no glowing review snippets for "Digital Fortress" itself should be warning to the reader. This is a poor book.
<br />
<br />Brown's NSA seems to be populated by petty egomaniacs with no respect for protocol and rules. We are introduced at the beginning of the novel to characters that are supposed to be mentally brilliant. Our heroine is supposed to have a 170 IQ and everyone around her is exceptional in one way or another. Yet none of them can think clearly, and all seem to be severely emotionally retarded. Suffice it to say that identifying with, or forming an attachment to, any of the characters is not possible.
<br />
<br />The author gets the characters to use a lot of tech and crypto buzz words in order to lend them credibility. He falls wide of the mark however and ends up displaying his own poor understanding of crypto, security and other technical matters. Any reader with more than a passing knowledge of any of the subject matter (you know who you are!) will be frustrated by the inaccuracies contained in the book.
<br />
<br />Truly interesting concepts are not explored in any depth. The issue of privacy would have been something that Brown could have discussed intelligently without needing to resort to ill informed techno babble.
<br />
<br />Readers who would like a techno thriller that's well researched and more involving are advised to look elsewhere. 
<br />
<br />Recommended are:
<br />
<br />"Cryptonomicon" by Neal Stephenson 
<br />(Has a WW2 and modern day element)
<br />
<br />"Snow Crash" by Neal Stephenson
<br />(Near future science fiction)
<br />
<br />"The Code Book" by Simon Singh
<br />(Excellent popular science treatment of cryptography, steganography and cloak and dagger down through the ages)
<br />
<br />"Applied Cryptography" by Bruce Schnier
<br />(Cryptography text by an industry expert and proponent of good public cryptography. This book is an education ;Â¬) )</span>
                  
